                    <msContents>

                        <summary>One autograph (?) copy of a trilingual Ottoman Turkish, Latin, and
                            Hungarian poetic risāle in praise of Islam by <persName
                                xml:lang="ota-Latn-x-lc">Murād the Interpreter</persName>.</summary>
                        <textLang mainLang="ota" otherLangs="hun lat">Ottoman Turkish, Hungarian,
                            and Latin, all three in both Latin and Arabic script</textLang>

                        <msItem xml:id="MS_Marsh_179-item1" n="1">
                            <author key="person_f8515">
                                <persName xml:lang="ota-Latn-x-lc">Tercümān Murād</persName>
                                <persName xml:lang="ota">ترجمان مراد</persName>
                                <lb/>
                                <persName xml:lang="ota-Latn-x-lc">Murād-ı tercümān</persName>
                                <persName xml:lang="ota">مراد ترجمان</persName>
                                <lb/>
                                <persName xml:lang="ota-Latn-x-lc">Murād Beğ bin
                                    ʹAbdüllāh</persName>
                                <persName xml:lang="ota">مراد بگ بن عبد الله</persName>
                                <lb/>
                                <persName xml:lang="ota-Latn-x-lc">Murād the Interpreter</persName>
                                <lb/>
                                <persName xml:lang="hun">Balázs Somlyai</persName>
                            </author>
                            <title key="work_23424" xml:lang="eng" type="desc">trilingual Ottoman Turkish,
                                Latin, and Hungarian poetic risāle in praise of Islam</title>
                            <title key="work_23424" xml:lang="lat">Hymnus Turcicé, Latiné et Hungaricé</title>
                            <rubric>دیباچه در سبب تالیف رساله</rubric>
                            <incipit>بسم الله الرحم الرحیم</incipit>
                            <incipit>چو بسم الله ایله سوره کیرلدی <lb/> پس آنی دڭلمك لازم
                                کورلدی</incipit>
                            <note>A prose note in three languages on <locus from="3a">folio
                                    3a</locus> identifies the text and suggests it is an autograph,
                                whence the Ottoman Turkish reads: <quote>بو رساله اوج دیل اوزره
                                    منظوم تطبیق اولنمشدر ترجمان مراد الندن ترجمه اتمك و یازمق
                                    یونندن</quote></note>
                            <note>A facsimile of this manuscript is available in <ref
                                    target="https://doi.org/10.1515/9783111412221"> Babinger et al.,
                                    1927</ref>.</note>
                            <listBibl>
                                <bibl><ref
                                        target="https://menadoc.bibliothek.uni-halle.de/ssg/content/pageview/775171"
                                        >Ethé, Hermann. <title>Catalogue of the Persian, Turkish,
                                            Hindûstânî and Pushtû Manuscripts in the Bodleian
                                            Library, Part II: Turkish, Hindûstânî, Pushtû and
                                            Additional Persian Manuscripts</title>. Oxford:
                                        Clarendon Press. 1930. col. 1206 § (96) 2134.</ref></bibl>
                                <bibl><ref target="https://doi.org/10.1515/9783111412221"> Babinger,
                                        Franz, Gragger, Robert, Mittwoch, Eugen and Mordtmann, J.
                                        H.. Literaturdenkmäler aus Ungarns Türkenzeit: Nach
                                        Handschriften in Oxford und Wien, Berlin, Boston: De
                                        Gruyter, 1927.
                                    </ref></bibl>
                            </listBibl>
                            <textLang mainLang="ota" otherLangs="hun lat">Ottoman Turkish,
                                Hungarian, and Latin, all three in both Latin and Arabic
                                script</textLang>
                        </msItem>

                    </msContents>
